    <h1>Blind, But Leading the Blind</h1>
    <p>
      When Sabriye Tenberken lost her vision at the age of 12, many doubted her future. But Sabriye saw a different path. Determined to bring change, she studied Central Asian studies and learned Tibetan — eventually developing the first Braille script for the Tibetan language.
    </p>
    <p>
      In 1998, she co-founded the school *Braille Without Borders* in Tibet to empower blind children through education and self-confidence. Sabriye has shown the world that blindness doesn’t mean helplessness — and sometimes, the people who’ve lost their sight are the ones who can help others truly see.
    </p>

